Package org.ejbca.core.ejb.authentication.cli

Enum CliAuthenticationTokenReferenceRegistry

  • java.lang.Object
    • java.lang.Enum<CliAuthenticationTokenReferenceRegistry>
      • org.ejbca.core.ejb.authentication.cli.CliAuthenticationTokenReferenceRegistry
  • All Implemented Interfaces:
    Serializable, Comparable<CliAuthenticationTokenReferenceRegistry>
    public enum CliAuthenticationTokenReferenceRegistry
extends Enum<CliAuthenticationTokenReferenceRegistry>
    Due to being sent over remote, this token needs to protect against two threats: replay and interception. Replay is stopped via the CliAuthenticationTokenReferenceRegistry, where each authentication token must register prior to its first authorization. Once authorized the token is removed from that registry, and further attempts to authorize the same token will fail. In order to allow the same token to be used several times within the local environment, the transient 'isVerified'-flag is set upon the first authorization. Interception of this token being transmitted risks making the password hash known, which can be used to forge future tokens. To guard against this threat, the password hash is never transmitted in cleartext. Instead a SHA1 hash is calculated on server side, registered here but not transmitted back (see CliAuthenticationToken's clone method). Meanwhile, on the client side the SHA1 hash is recalculated and stored in the token, and at authorization the two are compared to make sure that the token is valid. Note that this implies that true athentication (password comparison) is not performed until the first authorization act.
